    <h1>Duke Energy (DUK)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of Duke Energy Corporation — using FY2025 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 18, 2026 · Data: FY2025 10-K</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(revenue2025 / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(ocf2025 / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${eps2025.toFixed(2)}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">26.8%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF (Utility Model)</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. However, utility companies like Duke Energy have consistently negative free cash flow due to massive infrastructure capital expenditures. Therefore, we use an adjusted Operating Cash Flow as a proxy for structural free cash flow, deducting estimated maintenance capex.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Determine the Base Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Duke Energy generated <strong>${(ocf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong> in operating cash flow in FY2025. We estimate maintenance capex to be roughly ${(estimatedMaintenanceCapex / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion, leaving an adjusted free cash flow base of <strong>${(fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow the proxy FCF at <strong>4% per year</strong> for 5 years. This aligns with regulated rate base growth and typical utility earnings growth expectations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume growth stabilizes at <strong>2% forever</strong> — roughly mirroring long-term inflation and GDP growth. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount to present value</h4>
      <p>Future cash flows are discounted at <strong>7%</strong> — a reasonable required rate of return for a stable, regulated utility company. The 10-Year Treasury yield is currently 4.18%, meaning we are requiring a ~2.8% equity risk premium for this low-beta stock.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Subtract Debt, Divide by Shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value minus Net Debt ($90.6B) equals Equity Value. Dividing by shares outstanding (777M) provides the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF relies on future estimates. Here are our exact choices for Duke Energy and why we made them.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">4%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Regulated utilities grow earnings primarily through rate base expansion. Duke Energy has a massive capital plan focused on clean energy transition and grid modernization, supporting steady, approved rate increases. 4% is a conservative, highly achievable estimate.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">7%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        With the 10Y Treasury at 4.18%, a 7% required return is standard for regulated utilities given their low volatility and predictable cash flows. A higher discount rate would be overly punitive for a monopoly business.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is around 2-3%. A 2% perpetuity growth rate assumes Duke Energy will grow slightly below GDP over the long run, simply keeping pace with inflation and population growth in its territories.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

