  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Favorable regulatory outcomes:</strong> Higher allowed returns on equity (ROE) from state commissions.</li>
    <li><strong>Data center demand:</strong> Surge in power demand from AI data centers in their service territories.</li>
    <li><strong>Interest rate cuts:</strong> A lower rate environment makes utility dividends more attractive and reduces debt servicing costs.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Regulatory pushback:</strong> Denied rate increases hindering the recovery of massive capital investments.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher for longer interest rates:</strong> Increases the cost of their enormous debt load ($90B+) and makes their dividend yield less competitive.</li>
    <li><strong>Weather events:</strong> Severe storms (hurricanes in the Carolinas/Florida) causing extensive unrecoverable damages.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an adjusted Operating Cash Flow instead of Free Cash Flow?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Utility companies typically have negative Free Cash Flow because they spend aggressively on capital expenditures (building plants, upgrading grids). If we used strict FCF, the intrinsic value would be profoundly negative. By using Operating Cash Flow and deducting only "maintenance" capex (the cost to maintain current assets, ignoring expansion capex), we get a better picture of the underlying cash generation capacity of the business.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is Duke Energy a good investment?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Utilities are typically "widow and orphan" stocks—bought for stable dividends rather than explosive capital appreciation. Whether DUK is a good investment depends on your need for yield, your view on interest rates, and your risk tolerance. This DCF is just one tool to determine if the stock is priced fairly.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

